{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17489564","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17489564"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T04:21:40+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T04:21:40+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"692"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"692","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/692"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.03,0.15,0.67,0.01,0.14]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"692"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"106303"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"692","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/692"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"692"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"88771"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"34"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"73"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"570"},{"type":"tags","id":"1244"},{"type":"tags","id":"2079"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"7394"},{"type":"contributions","id":"7424"},{"type":"contributions","id":"9645"},{"type":"contributions","id":"13614"},{"type":"contributions","id":"14817"},{"type":"contributions","id":"14834"},{"type":"contributions","id":"14839"},{"type":"contributions","id":"17830"},{"type":"contributions","id":"39080"},{"type":"contributions","id":"39081"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"106303","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/106303"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 56-year-old man presents to the Emergency Department following a car crash. He complains of severe pain in his left arm and is unable to move it due to the pain. He has no significant medical history and does not take any regular medications.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears unwell. His pulse rate is 90/min, blood pressure 130/80 mmHg, respiratory rate 18/min, SpO2 98% on room air, and temperature 36.7\u00b0C. He has marked tenderness and swelling over the left proximal humerus, with a limited range of movement. His left arm appears to be slightly shorter than the right, and there is a noticeable deformity in the area of the proximal humerus. There is no numbness, change in colour or paralysis on examination of his left arm. An X-ray is shows a proximal humeral shaft fracture with 40\u00b0 displacement (Image).\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate management option?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Arthroplasty","Intramedullary nailing","Open reduction and internal fixation","Prolonged immobilisation","Sling immobilisation followed by early mobilisation"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe X-ray demonstrates a simple two-part surgical neck fracture of the left humerus, displaced and angulated by approximately 40 degrees. Large randomised controlled trials and meta-analyses provide moderate certainty evidence that compared to surgical treatment, non-surgical management does not result in worse clinical outcomes at 1 or 2 years for people with proximal humeral shaft fractures (without described displacement of \u0026gt;50\u00b0 or \u0026gt;1cm).\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003ENon-operative management with\u003Cstrong\u003E sling immobilisation\u003C/strong\u003E followed by early mobilisation is the most appropriate management option for this patient. This approach allows for adequate stabilisation of the fracture while promoting early range of motion, which is crucial for optimal recovery. It should be noted that, unlike the management of many other fracture types, proximal humeral fractures that meet the criteria for conservative management do not require reduction acutely, and instead reduction occurs over the first one to two weeks as the elbow hangs dependent and gravity alone \u201creduces\u201d or improve fracture alignment.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ENon-operative management\u003C/strong\u003E of proximal humeral fractures typically includes:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Col\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EImmobilisation\u003C/strong\u003E: The arm may be placed in a sling to allow for healing and to minimize movement.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPain management\u003C/strong\u003E: Use of analgesics (e.g., paracetamol, NSAIDs, opioids if severe) to manage pain and discomfort.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPhysical therapy\u003C/strong\u003E: Initiation of gentle range-of-motion exercises as healing progresses to maintain function and prevent stiffness, typically starting after a few weeks of immobilization.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EFollow-up imaging\u003C/strong\u003E: Regular assessments through follow-up appointments and imaging (X-rays at 10-14 days to confirm reduction) to monitor healing and alignment.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ol\u003E\u003Cp\u003ESurgical intervention may be considered instead of non-operative management for the following reasons:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Col\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDisplacement\u003C/strong\u003E: If the fracture is significantly displaced or angulated (\u0026gt;50\u00b0 or \u0026gt;1cm), surgical fixation may be required to restore proper alignment and function.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EComminution\u003C/strong\u003E: In cases of complex or comminuted fractures, where there are multiple fracture fragments, surgery may be necessary to stabilise the bone and provide adequate support.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EJoint Involvement\u003C/strong\u003E: If the fracture involves the shoulder joint (e.g., head or neck fractures) leading to instability, surgical intervention may be needed to maintain joint function.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EFailure of conservative treatment\u003C/strong\u003E: If non-operative management fails to provide adequate pain relief or function after an appropriate duration, surgery may be indicated to correct the issue.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ol\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EProlonged immobilisation\u003C/strong\u003E is not recommended as it has been shown to result in increased levels of pain, as well as reduced long-term function and range of motion. The benefits of early mobilisation in fracture healing and prevention of joint stiffness are well-established.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EOpen reduction and internal fixation (ORIF)\u003C/strong\u003E is generally reserved for specific indications such as older patients with proximal humeral fracture dislocations, fractures of the articular surface, and patients with significant humeral displacement. In this case, given the nature of the fracture and the patient\u0027s age, ORIF is not the first-line treatment.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIntramedullary nailing\u003C/strong\u003E may be utilised for surgical neck fractures which have failed conservative management by sling immobilisation, in 3-part proximal humerus fractures, or for combined proximal humerus and humeral shaft fractures. It is not the initial treatment of choice for this patient\u0027s fracture pattern.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EArthroplasty\u003C/strong\u003E in this age group only has evidence for use in complex fracture-dislocations or head-splitting fractures that fail initial fixation. It would be an overly aggressive approach for this simple two-part fracture.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIn conclusion, while surgical options remain available for specific indications, the current evidence supports non-operative management for most two-part proximal humeral fractures. This approach minimises surgical risks while providing comparable functional outcomes in the majority of cases. The decision between operative and non-operative management of proximal humeral fractures however, depends on the fracture type, displacement, patient factors, and overall functional goals.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["The majority of proximal humeral fractures can be safely managed non-operatively.","Early mobilisation following sling immobilisation is preferred over prolonged immobilisation for proximal humeral fractures.","Surgical intervention for proximal humeral fractures is generally reserved for specific indications such as significant displacement or articular involvement."],"references":["Torchia M. Proximal Humerus Fractures - Trauma - Orthobullets [Internet]. Orthobullets.com. 2019. Available at: https://www.orthobullets.com/trauma/1015/proximal-humerus-fractures","Handoll H, Elliott J, Thillemann TM, Aluko P, Brorson S. Interventions for treating proximal humeral fractures in adults. Cochrane Database Syst Rev. Updated June 21, 2022. Accessed December 16, 2022. https://doi.org/10.1002/14651858.CD000434.pub5","Rangan A, Handoll H, Brealey S, et al. Surgical vs nonsurgical treatment of adults with displaced fractures of the proximal humerus: the PROFHER randomized clinical trial. JAMA. 2015;313(10):1037\u20131047. doi:10.1001/jama.2015.1629","Brorson S, Palm H. Proximal humeral fractures: the choice of treatment. In: Falaschi P, Marsh D. Orthogeriatrics. 2020: 143\u2013153. https://doi.org/10.1007/978-3-030-48126-1_10"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"88771"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"692"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"ty